1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Bd3 Nf6 6. O-O Qc7 7. c4 {This
move is not so strong, as Black can play Nc6 directly.} Nc6 8. Nxc6 (8. Be3 Ne5
{The threat now is Neg4.} 9. h3 b6 $5 {The idea is now to play Bb7 followed by
d6 and Be7. Whenever White plays f4, we will take the bishop on d3. Later we
can put our f6 knight on d7 and transfer the e7 bishop to f6.} 10. f4 Nxd3 (
10... Nxc4 $2 11. Qc1 {with an idea b3}) 11. Qxd3 Bb7 12. Nd2 (12. Nc3 $6 {
This allows us the very interesting and active move...} Bb4 $1 13. e5 Bxc3 14.
Qxc3 Ne4 {The knight is very strong on e4.} 15. Qa3 {Stopping 0-0.} f6 $1 {An
important break in the centre.} 16. exf6 gxf6 $11 {With the rook coming to g8,
there will be pressure down the 'g' file. and the Black king is pretty safe in
the centre.}) 12... d6 13. Rae1 Be7 {And Black will 0-0 soon and follow the
plan that we previously mentioned - of Nd7 and Bf6.}) 8... dxc6 $1 {A very
important move: bc6 will be preferred when we actually can play d5 in the
centre. Here it will not be possible to play d5, so it makes more sense to
take with the 'd' pawn. This helps us to speed up our development with e5, and
our c8 bishop develops easily.} 9. f4 {Looks logical in order to play e5.} e5
$1 {An extremely strong move, nipping White's idea in the bud with e5. And, at
the same time, we keep the option of developing the bishop on c5.} 10. f5 (10.
fxe5 Ng4 11. Qe2 Bc5+ 12. Kh1 Qxe5 $17) 10... Bc5+ 11. Kh1 h5 $1 {The knight
is coming to g4, irrespective of whether or not White plays h3.} 12. Qe2 Ng4 {
This is an extremely unpleasant guest in White's position. The bishop on c5
and the knight on g4 cover a lot of dark squares in White territory.} 13. Nd2 (
13. Bg5 {With the idea of Bh4 would have been a better option for White.})
13... Qb6 (13... Qd8 {Is a typical idea to attack the d3 bishop and also
threaten Qh4; but it makes more sense when White has his knight on c3.} 14. Nf3
Nf2+ 15. Rxf2 Bxf2 16. Nxe5 $44) 14. g3 Nf2+ 15. Kg2 Nxd3 16. Qxd3 Bd4 17. Rb1
c5 $1 {The bishop on d4 is a powerhouse in this position and the other bishop
will be well placed on c6, attacking e4, while it's very difficult for the
knight to come to the d5 square. Black won a very nice game.} 18. a3 Bd7 19. b4
Ba4 20. Nf3 O-O-O 21. Be3 Bxe3 22. Qxe3 f6 23. bxc5 Qa5 24. Rb6 Rd7 25. Rd6 Rc7
26. Rd5 Bc6 27. Rd6 Ba4 28. Rd5 Bc6 29. Rc1 Kb8 30. Nd2 Rhc8 31. Nb3 Qxa3 32.
Rd3 Qb4 33. Rdc3 Ba4 34. Rb1 Ka8 35. Qf3 Rd7 36. Kh3 Bxb3 37. Rcxb3 Qxc5 38.
Rc1 Qd4 39. Qe2 Rc5 40. Qxh5 Ka7 41. Qe2 Qd2 42. Qf1 Qh6+ 43. Kg4 Qg5+ 44. Kf3
Qh5+ {Conclusion: it is important to understand that 7.c4 is weaker than 7.Qe2
and that Black can equalise effectively with Nc6! followed by taking with dc6
and e5.} 0-1

