1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Bd3 Nf6 6. O-O Qc7 7. Qe2 d6 8. c4
g6 9. Nc3 Bg7 {We reach the main position of our system. In this game, White
goes for the Nf3 and Bf4 plan.} 10. Nf3 {Why does White retreat his knight
back to f3? Well, the main reason is that he would like to play something like
Bf4 followed by e5. Black, on the other hand, will not let White do that.} O-O
11. Bf4 Nh5 $1 {With this move, Black prevents White from playing e5.} 12. Be3
{This looks like the most natural move, but the problem is that Black can now
sacrifice his bishop on g7 for the knight on c3. I call it a sacrifice because
it is such an important bishop that we are giving up. But then why are we
giving it up? It's for the sole reason that we can have clarity of play
afterwards. We can put our pawns on dark square and play against White's weak
pawns.} (12. Bd2 {Is much more conservative, as now we cannot ruin White's
pawn structure. But we can now continue normally with...} Nd7 13. Rac1 b6 14.
Rfd1 Bb7 15. Bg5 (15. Be3 Nhf6) 15... h6 16. Be3 Nhf6 17. h3 (17. Qd2 Ng4)
17... Nc5 18. Bd2 Rac8 19. b3 Rfd8 {Black has a decent, playable position.})
12... Bxc3 $1 13. bxc3 {So what do we have here? Black has given up his strong
bishop for what? 1. The c pawns are very weak. 2.c5 is an excellent outpost
for a Black knight. 3. Black has a ready-made idea of placing his pawns on
dark squares like e5 and f6 and then attacking the c4 pawn. All in all, thanks
to this Bc3 idea, the game takes on a very concrete character; and if you are
well versed in the ideas, then you can surely play such positions better than
your opponents - as Ivanchuk has shown on many occasions.} e5 14. Rfd1 Bg4 (
14... Nd7 {With the idea of Nc5 followed by f6 and Be6 is also an interesting
plan.}) 15. h3 Bxf3 16. Qxf3 Nd7 17. Bf1 Rad8 18. Bg5 f6 19. Bh6 Ng7 {Black
has consolidated his position and the main problem for White is that he cannot
really open up his position for the two bishops. Hence, in the long run, the
two knights will outperform the White bishops.} 20. Rd2 Nc5 21. Rad1 Qc6 22.
Rd5 Rf7 {Black plays carefully: removes his g7 knight from the pin, so that
next move he can go to e6.} 23. Qe3 Nge6 24. g3 Rfd7 25. Bg2 {Defending e4 but
forgetting about control of the c4 square.} (25. h4 {The idea of Bh3 is met
with...} Nc7 $1 $15) 25... Na4 $1 26. Qf3 Kf7 (26... Rf7 {Would have been more
accurate when the advantage is with Black.}) 27. h4 Ke7 28. c5 (28. h5 Qxc4 $15
) 28... Naxc5 (28... dxc5 $15) 29. h5 Qa4 30. Be3 b6 31. Qg4 Rg8 32. hxg6 hxg6
33. Bf3 Rdd8 34. Kg2 Rh8 35. Qxg6 Rdg8 36. Qf5 Ng7 37. Qg6 Ne8 38. Qf5 Ng7 39.
Qg6 Ne8 40. Qf5 1/2-1/2

