g6 9. Nc3 Bg7 10. Rd1 {This time instead of Nf3, Leko goes for Rd1 - but it
doesn't change much.} O-O 11. Nf3 {And now not following the normal
development of knight to d7, but the more active development with Nc6.} Nc6 12.
h3 (12. Bf4 {Will be seen in the game Svidler-Ivanchuk.}) 12... Nd7 {The f6
knight makes way for the bishop to sacrifice itself on c3.} 13. Be3 {When a
player like Leko plays White, it is clear that it wasn't the case that he
didn't consider the Bc3 move - it's just that he feels the position will be
complex enough to give him chances. Hence he doesn't deem it necessary to make
an uncomfortable move like Bd2.} Bxc3 $1 {As always, Ivanchuk stays true to
this idea in the Paulsen.} 14. bxc3 {What now follows is what we must learn
from Ivanchuk: how to play after the bishop is given up. The ideal setup as we
know is e5-f6-Be6-Nc5-Qf7 - maybe followed by Na5 with excellent pressure on
the c4 pawn. Ivanchuk first starts with f6, but he could have just as well
started with e5.} f6 (14... e5 $6 {When White sees the weakness of the d5
square and plays...} 15. Ne1 Nc5 $6 16. Bxc5 dxc5 17. Nc2 {And the White
knight enters d5 via e3, when White has an edge.}) 15. Qd2 Rd8 {First
defending the d6 pawn.} 16. Bc2 Nc5 {White's main problem is his light-squared
bishop. What exactly should he do about it?} 17. Nd4 Na5 $1 {Ivanchuk goes
after the c4 pawn. Black is already in the driving seat. With moves like e5
Be6 and Qf7 coming up, the c4 pawn is a goner!} 18. Qe2 e5 19. Nf3 Be6 $17 20.
Nd2 Qf7 21. f4 {Leko knows that he has lost the opening battle, so he tries to
muddy the waters.} Rac8 (21... Nxc4 22. f5 gxf5 23. exf5 Bd5 24. Nxc4 Bxc4 25.
Qf2 Rac8 26. Bxc5 dxc5 27. Rxd8+ Rxd8 28. Qxc5 Rd2 {Gives Black an excellent
position. Just shows that in these rapid time controls, sometimes it's not
possible to take the game to its logical conclusion.}) 22. Rab1 Nxc4 (22...
exf4 23. Bxf4 Nxc4 24. Nxc4 Bxc4 {Would have given Black a clear advantage, as
the a2 pawn hangs, too.}) 23. f5 gxf5 24. exf5 Bd5 25. Nxc4 Bxc4 26. Qg4+ Kh8
27. Rb6 {White has some compensation now.} Bd5 (27... d5 {Was also possible.})
28. Qh4 Bc6 29. Rb4 Rg8 30. Rg4 Qe7 31. Qh6 d5 32. Kh2 Nd7 33. Bb3 Qf7 34. Bf2
Rxg4 35. hxg4 Rg8 36. Kh3 Rg7 37. Bh4 Kg8 38. Rd3 Kf8 39. Rg3 Ke8 40. g5 Nc5
41. Bd1 Bd7 42. Bh5 Bxf5+ 43. Kh2 Rg6 44. Bxg6 Qxg6 45. Qxg6+ hxg6 46. gxf6 Kf7
47. Re3 Ne4 48. Kg1 b5 49. Kf1 g5 50. Rxe4 Bxe4 51. Bxg5 Bg6 52. Ke2 Ke6 53.
Ke3 Kf5 54. Bh4 Kg4 55. Bf2 Kg5 56. Kd2 Kxf6 57. Bc5 Bb1 58. a3 Kf5 59. Ke3 Be4
60. g3 Bg2 61. Bb4 Bh3 62. Bc5 Bg4 63. Bb4 Ke6 64. Kd2 Kd7 65. Ba5 Kc6 66. Bb4
d4 67. cxd4 exd4 68. Ba5 Kc5 69. Kc2 Kc4 70. Kb2 Kd3 71. Bb4 Ke2 72. Kc1 d3 73.
Bc3 Be6 74. Bb4 Kf3 75. Kd2 Bf5 76. Ba5 Kxg3 77. Bb4 Kf3 78. Ba5 Ke4 79. Kc1
Ke3 80. Bd2+ Kd4 81. Kb2 Kc5 82. Ba5 Kc4 83. Bd2 Bg6 84. Ba5 {A highly
