g6 9. Nc3 Bg7 10. Rd1 O-O 11. Nf3 Nc6 12. Bf4 {This is the first time we are
seeing this move. The moves Nf3, Rd1 and Bf4 can become quite confusing. But
in the game with Leko and also against Karjakin, we saw White play h3 here. So
Ivanchuk tries to take advantage of the fact that h3 wasn't played, in order
to pin the knight on f3 with Bg4.} e5 $1 {Though this is an antipositional
move, it has a concrete idea. The point is to make use of the d4 square for
the c6 knight and, at the same time, the bishop can be developed to g4 -
removing the f3 knight which is the main defender of the d4 square.} 13. Be3 {
In order to reinforce the d4 square.} (13. Bg5 {Might seem more logical
because White attacks the knight on f6, which is the defender of the d5 square.
} Bg4 $1 {It turns out that that d4 is weaker than the d5 square.} 14. Bxf6 (
14. Nd5 $2 Nxd5 15. cxd5 Nd4 16. Qe3 Bxf3 17. gxf3 Qd7 $17 {Is a clear
advantage for Black.}) 14... Bxf6 $1 (14... Nd4 $2 15. Nxd4 $1 Bxe2 16. Nd5 $1
$16) 15. Nd5 Qd8 $1 16. Qe3 Nd4 $15 {Black has an advantage due to the pin
towards the d1 rook.}) 13... Bg4 14. h3 Nd4 $1 {Ivanchuk is extremely accurate.
} (14... Bxf3 15. Qxf3 {Gives White a pleasant position, as after...} Nd4 {He
is not forced to take on d4.} 16. Qg3 $14) 15. Bxd4 Bxf3 $1 16. Qxf3 exd4 17.
Nd5 (17. Ne2 Rfe8 {Gives Black decent counterplay. His idea is later to play
Nd7 with the knight coming either to e5 or c5.}) 17... Nxd5 18. cxd5 {After
precise moves by Black, we reach a position which is equal - excellent play by
Vassily Ivanchuk! In fact, you must look at how the game ended. With the help
of some pretty tactics, he was able to beat Peter Svidler.} Qb6 19. Rab1 Rfe8
20. Qg3 Rac8 21. h4 Rc5 22. h5 Bf6 23. f4 Rc2 $1 24. Kh2 Rxb2 25. Rxb2 Qxb2 26.
Rb1 Qd2 27. Rxb7 Re5 $3 28. f5 Bg5 29. Kh3 Bf4 30. Qf3 gxf5 31. g3 Be3 32. exf5
Qxd3 33. f6 Kf8 34. Rb3 Qc4 35. Qf5 Re8 36. Rb7 Qc1 37. g4 Bf4 {So the
conclusion is that if your opponent plays Bf4 prior to h3, then your solution
is to play e5 followed by Bg4 and plonk a knight into d4.} 0-1

