{After analysing five games by Vasily Ivanchuk, we have good ideas up our
sleeve as to what to do when our opponent plays Nf3 followed by h3 and Bf4 or
Rd1 followed by Nf3 and Bf4 and similar ideas. But what we don't know is what
to do if White plays naturally. i.e. if White is not interested in subtleties
and just plays Be3 Rac1 Rfd1 and goes into normal hedgehog play. Here we will
try to delve into such set-ups which have chances of occurring more often if
your opponent doesn't know much theory.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4
a6 5. Bd3 Nf6 6. O-O Qc7 7. Qe2 d6 8. c4 g6 9. Nc3 Bg7 10. Be3 {The normal,
natural developing move.} O-O (10... Nbd7 $5 {I recommend this mode of
development ahead of the normal 0-0. The point is that with the bishop on d3,
it makes sense to play Ne5 as quickly as possible. So we make that move even
before 0-0.} 11. Rac1 (11. f4 $5 {This move stops Ne5 but weakens the e4 pawn;
and later we can make the very thematic e5 move, securing that square for our
pieces.} O-O 12. Rac1 e5 $1 13. Nf3 exf4 14. Bxf4 Nc5 {After this, Black will
place his bishop on e6 - the other knight will go d7-e5.} (14... Qb6+ 15. Kh1
Nc5 16. Bb1 Be6 17. b3 Rad8 18. Rfd1 Rfe8 {Black has a nice tenable position:
White's e4 pawn is weak.})) 11... Ne5 {The main point of this move is that
it's not easy for White to follow the standard plan of f3, Rfd1,Qf2 ,b4,Nb3 -
as happened in the main game. The knight on e5 keeps putting unpleasant
pressure on White's position.} 12. f3 {This looks like the most natural move,
stopping Ng4.} (12. b3 Nfg4 $1 13. Bf4 Nxd3 14. Qxd3 e5 15. Nd5 Qb8 $15 {White
will have some compensation - but a piece is a piece!}) 12... O-O $1 13. Rfd1
b6 14. b4 {This should definitely be one of the key moves here. But it's not
so good now, as the c4 pawn becomes weak.} (14. b3 {Is not really scary.} Bb7
15. Bb1 Rfe8 16. Qf2 Rad8 (16... Rac8 $6 {Is met with the typical shot...} 17.
Ndb5 axb5 18. Nxb5 Qb8 19. Nxd6 $14) 17. h3 Bf8 {Gearing up for the d5 break
later.} 18. f4 Ned7 {And Black has a decent position.}) 14... Bb7 15. Nb3 Nfd7
{And Black has excellent coordination. One sample line could go like this...}
16. f4 Nxd3 17. Qxd3 Rfd8 18. Qxd6 Qxd6 19. Rxd6 Bf8 {Black will regain the
pawn or White will have sacrificed the exchange.}) 11. Rac1 {'The white rooks
go to their natural squares - c1 and d1. White will then play f3, Qf2 and Bf1,
